THE MOUNTAIN'S CROWN 2
A Chronicle of the Skyrim Wardens

PART I: THE BREAKER
The Inner Sanctum
The doors crashed open and the sound hit them like a wallΓÇöa deafening, rhythmic scream of metal tearing into stone. GRIND. THUD. GRIND. THUD. The air burned with the taste of copper and ozone, ancient dust pulverized into a choking haze that coated their tongues and stung their eyes.
In the center of the chamber, clamped directly onto the sacred relief of the High King's Vault, a massive boring machine churned. Brass gears spun and pistons fired, driving iron teeth into the ancient rock, powered by a cluster of soul gems that pulsed with a sick, radioactive green light.
Beside the machine stood a titan.
Seven feet of grey-green Orcish muscle loomed over the controls, encased in a suit of Ancient Dragonplate armor. The massive bone plates were bolted directly into his own skeletal systemΓÇöthe skin around the connection points scarred, weeping a translucent amber fluid. He smelled of pine resin and burning oil.
He continued his work as the doors crashed open. His massive, armored hands adjusted a delicate pressure valve on the drill with the steady precision of a watchmaker, ignoring the violent vibrations of the machine and the arrival of an army at his back.
Alfonso's sixteen plague thralls flooded through the doorway, spreading across the chamber in a wall of corrupted flesh. Galmar Stone-Fist strode in behind them, leveling his warhammer at the figure's back.
"FACE YOUR DEATH, ABOMINATION!"
The figure froze. His hand locked on the valve.
SlowlyΓÇöwith the heavy, hydraulic whine of a siege engine rotatingΓÇöhe turned.
His face was a landscape of ruin. His jaw had been replaced by the lower mandible of a Frost Troll, vented to release clouds of acrid gas. But it was his eyes that froze bloodΓÇöfaceted amber gems, crystallized into his sockets. They clicked audibly as they zoomed and focused, scanning each of them, analyzing the quality of their steel and the stance of their bodies.
The voice that emerged from his chest was deep, resonant, and utterly devoid of fear.
"The Crypt is breached. I calculated the rear guard would hold for another hour. You are persistent."
Galmar spat on the floor. "Surrender the ruin. Or we bury you in it."
The Orc tilted his head. The gem-eyes whirred, locking onto the Nord commander.
"Surrender? I am Ulag. I broke the walls of Bromjunaar. I broke the shield-wall of the Snow Elves. Why would I surrender to a noise?"
He took a step forward, and the stone floor cracked under his weight. He gestured to the drill behind him.
"The Nords locked their legitimacy behind a puzzle door. Matching symbols. Dragon claws. They treated power like a riddle to be solved. Pathetic."
He drew himself up to his full, towering height.
"Power is not a riddle. It is an equation of force. I do not play games with dead architects. I apply pressure until the structure fails."
The Analysis
His gem-eyes swept across the assembled force, clicking and recalculating. He did not look at the wall of plague thralls. He did not look at Galmar. His gaze swept past them as if they were irrelevant environmental clutter. His crystalline eyes whirred, clicked, and locked onto the Wardens. He saw the impossible energies they carried, and began his assessment.
He looked at Kyboh.
"The Maker's Mark. A self-contained kinetic loop. The final design. Hjolmar was busy after I went to sleep. Your vessel is inefficient, but the resonance is pure."
His gaze shifted to Alfonso, and something almost like a smile crossed his ruined face.
"A fascinating pathogen. Peryite's orderly rot, built onto Bal's chaotic gift. Your thralls outside stink of its potential. Unstable, but... efficient."
His eyes fell on Saijah, and his tone became cold, clinical.
"The Hawk's breath. A divine spark. An antibody in the system. Anomaly."
He looked between Orion and Davinia, assessing their shared undeath.
"And two ghosts. One, an immortal, still clinging to mortal sounds... and the other, a pretender in a Queen's crown, worn like a common headdress. You are all... statistically improbable variables."
While the monster talked, Galmar moved to Davinia's side, his shield held high. He spoke in a low, urgent rasp, never taking his eyes off Ulag.
"He's stalling. Look at the drill. Don't listen to him. We are here for ONE THING." He nodded sharply toward the vault door. "The Crown. The moment that vault is breached, we grab it. That's the only victory that matters today."
The Declaration
Ulag raised a massive, bolted hand and pointed not at them, but at the vault door being devoured by his machine.
"You believe that Crown is a symbol of leadership. You are mistaken. It is a tool. A control rod, forged to bypass the fatal flaw of your species: free will. Alduin's victory is inevitable. My purpose here is to ensure that when the World-Eater scours this land, a disciplined, efficient army of mortals stands ready to serve him in the world that comes after. That Crown will grant a worthy priest the unwavering loyalty of every Nord in this crypt."
He looked at Galmar and Hroki and the sixteen plague thralls.
"You understand. I am not killing them. I am recruiting them."
